{"cursor":"1960","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nIn the U.S. soap opera world, 'recurring status' is the status of a performer\nwho consistently performs in less than three episodes out of a five-day work\nweek, and is therefore let out of their multi-year contract in order for the\nshow to save money. Contract evaluations are done every quarter, and the actors\nthat don't meet their \"quota\" of episodes are in danger of being dropped from\ntheir contract and put on recurring status. Instead of paying a flat fee for the\nactor over a series of a few years, the actor is then paid a certain sum for\neach show in which he or she is needed.\n","linknr":100,"url":"Recurring_status","recorded":1363127385,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Recurring_status&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Recurring_status&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.wikihiero%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-head","#p-search","/wiki/File:Question_book-new.svg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","/wiki/Wikipedia:Citing_sources","/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability","//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Recurring_status&action=edit","/wiki/Help:Introduction_to_referencing/1","/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiabilit